# Jidoka: Hello Agent

[![Run in Livebook](https://livebook.dev/badge/v1/blue.svg)](https://livebook.dev/run?url=https%3A%2F%2Fraw.githubusercontent.com%2Fmikehostetler%2Fjidoka%2Fmain%2Flivebook%2F01_hello_agent.livemd)

This notebook is the first Jidoka onboarding notebook. It starts with the
smallest useful agent, then adds one deterministic tool, one workflow, and one
imported JSON agent.

Most cells are deterministic and do not require a provider key. The live chat
cells are optional and run only when `ANTHROPIC_API_KEY` is set. In Livebook,
a secret named `ANTHROPIC_API_KEY` is also supported through `LB_ANTHROPIC_API_KEY`.

## Setup

This notebook installs Jidoka from GitHub so it can run from LiveBook without a
local checkout.

```elixir
Mix.install(
  [
    {:jidoka, git: "https://github.com/mikehostetler/jidoka.git", branch: "main"}
  ],
  config: [
    jidoka: [
      model_aliases: %{
        fast: "anthropic:claude-haiku-4-5"
      }
    ]
  ]
)
```

```elixir
provider_env =
  ["ANTHROPIC_API_KEY", "LB_ANTHROPIC_API_KEY"]
  |> Enum.find_value(fn name ->
    case System.get_env(name) do
      nil -> nil
      "" -> nil
      key -> {name, key}
    end
  end)

provider_ready? = not is_nil(provider_env)

provider_env_source =
  case provider_env do
    nil ->
      :not_configured

    {name, key} ->
      System.put_env("ANTHROPIC_API_KEY", key)
      name
  end

provider_setup_hint =
  "Set ANTHROPIC_API_KEY, or a Livebook secret named ANTHROPIC_API_KEY"

%{
  jidoka_source: "https://github.com/mikehostetler/jidoka.git",
  provider_ready?: provider_ready?,
  provider_env_source: provider_env_source,
  model_aliases: Jidoka.model_aliases()
}
```

The tutorial keeps framework logs quiet so provider-backed cells show the result
instead of runtime internals. Set `show_runtime_logs?` to `true` when you want to
inspect Jido/Jidoka execution details.

```elixir
show_runtime_logs? = false

Logger.configure(level: if(show_runtime_logs?, do: :notice, else: :warning))
Jidoka.Runtime.debug(if(show_runtime_logs?, do: :on, else: :off))

format_chat_result = fn
  {:ok, turn} ->
    {:ok, Jido.AI.Turn.extract_text(turn)}

  {:error, reason} ->
    {:error, Jidoka.format_error(reason)}

  other ->
    other
end

%{
  runtime_logs: if(show_runtime_logs?, do: :notice, else: :warning),
  jidoka_debug: Jidoka.Runtime.debug()
}
```

```elixir
start_or_reuse = fn id, start_fun ->
  case Jidoka.whereis(id) do
    nil -> start_fun.()
    pid -> {:ok, pid}
  end
end
```

## Define The Smallest Useful Agent

A Jidoka agent has four public sections:

- `agent do` for stable identity and optional context schema
- `defaults do` for instructions and model
- `capabilities do` for tools and other model-reachable capabilities
- `lifecycle do` for runtime policy like hooks, guardrails, and memory

Only `agent.id` and `defaults.instructions` are needed for a basic agent.

```elixir
defmodule LivebookDemo.AssistantAgent do
  use Jidoka.Agent

  agent do
    id :livebook_assistant
    description "Minimal assistant used by the first Jidoka LiveBook."
  end

  defaults do
    model :fast
    instructions "You are a concise assistant. Answer directly."
  end
end
```

Inspect the compiled agent without making a model call:

```elixir
{:ok, definition} = Jidoka.inspect_agent(LivebookDemo.AssistantAgent)

Map.take(definition, [
  :kind,
  :id,
  :description,
  :model,
  :context,
  :tool_names,
  :subagent_names,
  :workflow_names,
  :handoff_names
])
```

## Optional Live Chat

This cell starts the agent and sends one message if a provider key is configured.
If the key is absent, it returns a skip tuple.

```elixir
if provider_ready? do
  {:ok, pid} =
    start_or_reuse.("livebook-assistant", fn ->
      LivebookDemo.AssistantAgent.start_link(id: "livebook-assistant")
    end)

  result = LivebookDemo.AssistantAgent.chat(pid, "Write one sentence about what Jidoka does.")
  format_chat_result.(result)
else
  {:skip, provider_setup_hint <> " to run provider-backed chat cells."}
end
```

## Add One Tool

Tools are deterministic application work exposed to the model as callable
actions. Jidoka tools use Zoi schemas and compile to Jido actions underneath.

```elixir
defmodule LivebookDemo.Tools.AddNumbers do
  use Jidoka.Tool,
    name: "add_numbers",
    description: "Adds two integers.",
    schema:
      Zoi.object(%{
        a: Zoi.integer(),
        b: Zoi.integer()
      }),
    output_schema:
      Zoi.object(%{
        sum: Zoi.integer()
      })

  @impl true
  def run(%{a: a, b: b}, _context) do
    {:ok, %{sum: a + b}}
  end
end
```

Run the tool directly:

```elixir
LivebookDemo.Tools.AddNumbers.run(%{a: 20, b: 22}, %{tenant: "demo"})
```

Attach the tool to an agent:

```elixir
defmodule LivebookDemo.MathAgent do
  use Jidoka.Agent

  agent do
    id :livebook_math_agent

    schema Zoi.object(%{
      tenant: Zoi.string() |> Zoi.default("demo"),
      session: Zoi.string() |> Zoi.optional()
    })
  end

  defaults do
    model :fast
    instructions "Use tools when they help. Keep the final answer short."
  end

  capabilities do
    tool LivebookDemo.Tools.AddNumbers
  end
end
```

Inspect the agent's context defaults and published tool names:

```elixir
%{
  context_defaults: LivebookDemo.MathAgent.context(),
  tool_names: LivebookDemo.MathAgent.tool_names()
}
```

Optional provider-backed tool call:

```elixir
if provider_ready? do
  {:ok, pid} =
    start_or_reuse.("livebook-math-agent", fn ->
      LivebookDemo.MathAgent.start_link(id: "livebook-math-agent")
    end)

  result =
    LivebookDemo.MathAgent.chat(pid, "Use the add_numbers tool to add 20 and 22. Reply with only the sum.",
      context: %{session: "livebook"}
    )

  format_chat_result.(result)
else
  {:skip, provider_setup_hint <> " to run provider-backed tool calls."}
end
```

## Add A Deterministic Workflow

Use workflows when application code should own an ordered process.

```elixir
defmodule LivebookDemo.Tools.DoubleNumber do
  use Jidoka.Tool,
    name: "double_number",
    description: "Doubles an integer.",
    schema:
      Zoi.object(%{
        value: Zoi.integer()
      }),
    output_schema:
      Zoi.object(%{
        value: Zoi.integer()
      })

  @impl true
  def run(%{value: value}, _context) do
    {:ok, %{value: value * 2}}
  end
end

defmodule LivebookDemo.Workflows.MathPipeline do
  use Jidoka.Workflow

  workflow do
    id :livebook_math_pipeline
    description "Adds one to a value and doubles the result."

    input Zoi.object(%{
            value: Zoi.integer()
          })
  end

  steps do
    tool :add, LivebookDemo.Tools.AddNumbers,
      input: %{
        a: input(:value),
        b: value(1)
      }

    tool :double, LivebookDemo.Tools.DoubleNumber,
      input: %{
        value: from(:add, :sum)
      }
  end

  output from(:double)
end
```

Inspect and run the workflow:

```elixir
{:ok, workflow} = Jidoka.inspect_workflow(LivebookDemo.Workflows.MathPipeline)
{:ok, debug} = Jidoka.Workflow.run(LivebookDemo.Workflows.MathPipeline, %{value: 20}, return: :debug)

%{
  workflow: Map.take(workflow, [:id, :description, :steps, :dependencies, :output]),
  run_output: debug.output,
  run_steps: debug.steps
}
```

Trigger a validation error and format it for a user:

```elixir
{:error, reason} = Jidoka.Workflow.run(LivebookDemo.Workflows.MathPipeline, %{value: "twenty"})
Jidoka.format_error(reason)
```

## Expose The Workflow To An Agent

Workflow capabilities let a model choose a deterministic process without owning
the process.

```elixir
defmodule LivebookDemo.WorkflowAgent do
  use Jidoka.Agent

  agent do
    id :livebook_workflow_agent
  end

  defaults do
    model :fast
    instructions "Use workflow tools for arithmetic processes. Return the final result clearly."
  end

  capabilities do
    workflow LivebookDemo.Workflows.MathPipeline,
      as: :run_math_pipeline,
      description: "Add one to an integer and double the result.",
      result: :structured
  end
end
```

```elixir
{:ok, definition} = Jidoka.inspect_agent(LivebookDemo.WorkflowAgent)

Map.take(definition, [:id, :tool_names, :workflow_names, :workflows])
```

Optional provider-backed workflow capability call:

```elixir
if provider_ready? do
  {:ok, pid} =
    start_or_reuse.("livebook-workflow-agent", fn ->
      LivebookDemo.WorkflowAgent.start_link(id: "livebook-workflow-agent")
    end)

  result = LivebookDemo.WorkflowAgent.chat(pid, "Use the run_math_pipeline workflow with value 20. What is the output?")
  format_chat_result.(result)
else
  {:skip, provider_setup_hint <> " to run provider-backed workflow capability calls."}
end
```

## Import A JSON Agent

Imported agents are constrained runtime specs. Executable capabilities resolve
through explicit registries supplied by the application.

```elixir
json =
  Jason.encode!(%{
    agent: %{
      id: "livebook_imported_math",
      description: "Imported math assistant",
      context: %{
        "tenant" => "demo",
        "channel" => "livebook"
      }
    },
    defaults: %{
      model: "fast",
      instructions: "Use available tools when they help. Keep answers short."
    },
    capabilities: %{
      tools: ["add_numbers"]
    }
  })

{:ok, imported_agent} =
  Jidoka.import_agent(json,
    available_tools: [LivebookDemo.Tools.AddNumbers]
  )

{:ok, imported_definition} = Jidoka.inspect_agent(imported_agent)

Map.take(imported_definition, [:id, :description, :context, :tool_names])
```

Encode the imported agent back to YAML:

```elixir
case Jidoka.encode_agent(imported_agent, format: :yaml) do
  {:ok, yaml} -> yaml
  {:error, reason} -> Jidoka.format_error(reason)
end
```

Optional provider-backed imported-agent chat:

```elixir
if provider_ready? do
  {:ok, pid} =
    start_or_reuse.("livebook-imported-agent", fn ->
      Jidoka.start_agent(imported_agent, id: "livebook-imported-agent")
    end)

  result =
    Jidoka.chat(pid, "Use the add_numbers tool to add 7 and 35. Reply with only the sum.",
      context: %{"session" => "livebook-imported"}
    )

  format_chat_result.(result)
else
  {:skip, provider_setup_hint <> " to run provider-backed imported-agent chat."}
end
```

## What To Learn Next

This notebook covered the core path:

- compiled agents
- tools
- context schemas
- deterministic workflows
- workflow capabilities
- imported agents
- structured errors
- inspection helpers

Next areas to explore:

- hooks and guardrails
- memory
- subagents and handoffs
- Ash resources
- MCP tools
- constrained web access
- `Jidoka.AgentView` with the Phoenix consumer app

Run the existing demos from the package directory:

```bash
mix jidoka chat --dry-run
mix jidoka workflow -- 7
mix jidoka orchestrator --dry-run
cd dev/jidoka_consumer && PORT=4002 mix phx.server
```
